        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We initially explored several bands, but after considering the SED of the source and the capabilities of ALMA in each band, we settled on band 6. We use the recommended (default) correlator setup for continuum observations in band 6.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The angular resolution was set so that the inner edge of the disk could be resolved. This is confirmed by the OST simulations of the smallest of our disk models. The largest scale was set by unresolved SCUBA-2 observations that restrict the outer edge of the disk to r &lt; 200 AU. At 31.5 pc, a disk of radius &lt; 200 AU will have a diameter of &lt; 12.7 arcseconds.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The total (unresolved) disk brightness in the sub-mm is known from observations with other instruments (JCMT/SCUBA-2), and could be easily extrapolated to the desired ALMA wavelength. To estimate the surface brightness, we generated three model images of this disk with a variety of plausible sizes. The faintest part (outer edge) of the faintest of these models was used to estimate the expected source brightness, and the desired sensitivity was set to give a good SNR for this source brightness. We simulated our observations of these three models with the ALMA OST and confirmed that they are detectable.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
