    <prp:abstract>Direct imaging of Earth-like planets in the habitable zones of other stars (exoEarths) will be complicated by exozodiacal dust (exozodi). Surveys with the Keck Interferometer Nuller (KIN) and the Large Binocular Telescope Interferometer (LBTI) are detecting this dust around some nearby stars, but a fundamental understanding of how exozodi arises is vital to fully assess the problem posed by this dust for exoEarth imaging. Belts of parent bodies--located far outside the terrestrial zones--are the likely source of exozodi. Studying these reservoirs is the key to elucidating the currently-unknown mechanism that supplies exozodi. Detailed imaging of cold parent body belts is a task only possible with ALMA. Gamma Ophiuchi, a nearby A0 star, is one of only five targets with exozodi detected by KIN. It also hosts a massive parent body belt, although the location, size, and morphology of this belt is unknown. We propose to image the parent body belt around Gamma Ophiuchi and use the results to advance our understanding of exozodi in this system and more broadly.</prp:abstract>
